{"id": "duc04-testb-23:4#14", "contents": "Brazilian officials have managed to calm the market by hinting at an impending aid program from the IMF, but are also maintaining that they do not need the cash and are in no hurry to receive it. However, US officials and top IMF officials are growing nervous, concerned that the longer the negotiations drag on, the greater the risk of Brazil being caught in another round of market turmoil. There is a real risk that the government may be forced to devalue its currency, which is currently pegged to the dollar, and has had to raise interest rates to over 50% to prevent a sudden devaluation, choking off credit for most companies and pushing the country into recession."}
